 font-size:13pt"> outrageously generous to itself with public money. The recent </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">Savil</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> scandal suggests the BBC can be sloppy and very evasive.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">There are more TV and Radio cha</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">nnels. The more channels there are, the more diluted the quality of the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> becomes. But probably Radio and local radio are doing better than TV.  </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">There are excellent </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> but fewer of them. Many believe the BBC has been </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">dumbing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> down. (We ha</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">d a black and white TV with one channel - The BBC - I was allowed to stay up for 'The Cherry Orchard'. Now there are many channels with no </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> like the Cherry Orchard.) It seems everything now has to be 'popular' on all channels.  BBC 4 was planned </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">as an 'Arts Channel'. But the 'arts' </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> have been watered down.  What is BBC 3 for? Reduce the hours broadcast and 'distill' the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> into more powerful and potent offerings. </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">Originally, 'heats' were broadcast weekly of 'Young musician of t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">he year'.  Now with more BBC channels, the whole competition is condensed into a couple of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> (with much time given to what the competitors ate for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">breakfast,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> and the like than their performances). Why?</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">The BBC News channel seems to compare badly </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">with Sky News, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">Algezeera</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">, France 24, and even CNN. The BBC must have the most extensive news network of any? Building themselves (at public expense) the grandest News studio in the world seems to have resulted in a less concise and less interesting station</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">.(</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">And why waste so much air time every 1/4 hour with the same trailer?)</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">Recently on BBC News International, for 12 hours, the main items of International news (every 15 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">mins</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">) were the stock market floatation of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">'Twitter' followed by the activities of the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">Mayor of Toronto.  </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">Radio 4 still seems to be excellent but even this station shows clear signs of </span><span style="font-f