lectures' - given by a transvestite dressed in a farcical dress with orange shoes, and absurdly overdone 'make-up', who sadly seemed to have nothing of consequence to say, broadcast at 9.00am! Who i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">s the DG trying to kid?</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">Yes. Surely far too many </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> do not relate in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">anyway</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> to the high ideals of the Charter. </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">Impartiality.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">  Many claim the BBC is politically biased. Probably the balance is not quite right.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">The BBC should have unlimited</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> scope, scale and remit within their financial constraints.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">With several channels and stations, 'particular audiences' should be catered for. In the early days of TV, one single national station was able to cater for diverse national interests: excelle</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">nt international and national news coverage, serious discussions, political debate, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">visits</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> to live theatre, opera, farce, satire, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">humour</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">, light entertainment, and many major sporting events. </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">What ever</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> produces the best quality </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> at the best v</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">alue for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> fee </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">payers.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> It is probably better to pay other (less profligate) </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">, to make as many </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> as possible for us.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">The BBC must have the largest collection of radio and TV archives in the world and as all these </span><span style="font-family:Ver